    </p>
    <p>
      The problem: most hail damage isn't visible from the ground. Homeowners assume their roof is fine,
      skip the inspection, and find out two years later when a leak shows up in their ceiling — well outside
      the insurance filing window. This guide covers how to spot hail damage, what to do next, and what it
      actually costs to fix in Salt Lake County in 2026.
    </p>

    <h2>How Utah Hailstorms Damage Roofs</h2>

    <p>
      Asphalt shingles are the dominant roofing material in Salt Lake County. When hailstones — even
      smaller ones in the 3/4" to 1" range — strike shingles at velocity, they knock the protective
      granule coating off the surface. Those granules aren't decorative. They're the shingle's UV
      protection and waterproofing layer. Once they're gone, the asphalt mat underneath is exposed to
      sun and moisture, and shingle lifespan drops dramatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      Larger hail (1.5"+, which is not unusual in SLC metro summer storms) can crack the shingle mat
      entirely, creating direct water intrusion points. This kind of damage can start leaking
      immediately or take months to show up inside the home.
    </p>

    <h3>Why Sandy and South County Get Hit Hard</h3>
    <p>
      The Point of the Mountain area between Salt Lake and Utah counties acts as a storm convergence
      zone. Summer thunderstorm cells that build over Utah County frequently track northeast along
      the Wasatch Front, hitting Sandy, Draper, and Cottonwood Heights with their full intensity
      before weakening over the valley floor. It's not uncommon for a storm to cause significant
      hail damage in Sandy while barely affecting downtown Salt Lake City.
    </p>

    <h2>How to Tell If Your Roof Has Hail Damage</h2>

    <p>
      You don't have to get on the roof to find the first indicators. Start on the ground with these
      checks, then call for a professional inspection.
    </p>

    <div class="damage-checklist">
      <h3>✅ Ground-Level Hail Damage Checklist</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Dents or dings on metal gutters and downspouts</li>
        <li>Dents on AC condenser fins (metal fins on the outdoor unit)</li>
        <li>Granules collected in gutters or in downspout splash areas (looks like coarse sand)</li>
        <li>Dents on wood fascia or painted trim</li>
        <li>Damage to window screens, sills, or shutters</li>
        <li>Damage to deck furniture, fencing, or vehicles parked outside</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>
      If you're seeing any of these, there's a very high probability your shingles took a hit too.
      The next step is a roof-level inspection by a licensed contractor who knows what hail impact
      marks look like on asphalt shingles specifically.
    </p>

    <h3>What Hail Damage Looks Like on Shingles</h3>
    <p>
      On asphalt shingles, hail impact leaves random circular marks (not in any pattern — random
      is the key word that distinguishes hail from normal blistering or wear). The granules are
      missing in the impact area, and the dark asphalt mat underneath is visible. Fresh impacts
      look shiny. Older impacts look weathered and dark. A contractor experienced with insurance
      work knows the difference and knows how to document it correctly.
    </p>

    <div class="callout warning">
      <p><strong>Don't wait for a leak to confirm damage.</strong> Hail-damaged shingles often don't
      leak immediately. The water intrusion can start months or years later — by which time your
      insurance filing window has closed. Get an inspection booked while the damage is fresh and documentable.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What to Do After a Hailstorm in Salt Lake County</h2>

    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">1</div>
        <h3>Document the Storm</h3>
        <p>Note the date of the storm and save any weather alerts or news reports about hail in your area. Your insurer will verify the event.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">2</div>
        <h3>Check Ground-Level Indicators</h3>
        <p>Look at gutters, AC unit, downspouts. Damage here strongly supports a roof damage claim.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">3</div>
        <h3>Call for a Free Inspection</h3>
        <p>A licensed contractor gets on the roof and documents the damage with photos and measurements before your insurance adjuster visit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">4</div>
        <h3>File the Claim</h3>
        <p>With contractor documentation in hand, file with your insurer. Don't file without documentation — it weakens the claim.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>The Insurance Claim Process for Utah Roof Damage</h2>

    <p>
      Most Utah homeowners insurance policies cover storm damage to roofs under the dwelling coverage
      portion of the policy. Here's how the process works once you've documented damage:
    </p>

    <h3>Step 1: File Your Claim</h3>
    <p>
      Contact your insurer and report the storm damage. They'll assign a claim number and schedule
      an adjuster visit. Utah insurers generally require claims within 12 months of the storm event —
      and some policies have tighter windows, so check your policy language.
    </p>

    <h3>Step 2: Adjuster Visit</h3>
    <p>
      An adjuster will come out to assess the damage and determine if it meets the threshold for a
      covered claim. Having a contractor-prepared damage report before this visit is the single most
      important thing you can do to protect your claim. Adjusters work quickly and can miss damage
      that a contractor who has spent an hour on the roof will catch.
    </p>

    <h3>Step 3: The Settlement Offer</h3>
    <p>
      The insurer issues an Actual Cash Value (ACV) estimate, which accounts for depreciation. If
      your roof is 15 years old, they may only offer a fraction of replacement cost up front. Most
      policies have a Replacement Cost Value (RCV) provision that pays the remaining "recoverable
      depreciation" once the work is completed and documented. Make sure your contractor understands
      how to work within RCV/ACV policies.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>You're allowed to negotiate.</strong> If the adjuster's estimate doesn't match your
      contractor's documented scope, you can dispute it. A contractor who works insurance claims
      regularly will help you navigate this process — including supplementing the claim if additional
      damage is found during the repair.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Hail Damage Roof Repair Costs in Salt Lake County (2026)</h2>

    <p>
      What you'll pay out of pocket depends on your deductible and the extent of the damage. Here's
      what actual repair work costs in the SLC metro area in 2026:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Partial hail damage repair (one section or slope):</strong> $1,500 – $4,500</li>
      <li><strong>Full roof replacement — 1,500 sq ft home:</strong> $8,000 – $14,000</li>
      <li><strong>Full roof replacement — 2,500 sq ft home:</strong> $13,000 – $22,000</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency tarping (while claim processes):</strong> $300 – $800</li>
      <li><strong>Hail damage inspection:</strong> Free from most contractors who do insurance work</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      If damage is covered by insurance, your actual cost is your deductible — typically $1,000 to
      $2,500. The insurer covers the rest. This is why prompt documentation matters: the difference
      between a properly filed claim and a missed window is thousands of dollars out of pocket.
    </p>

