    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I know if my roof has hail damage in Utah?</h3>
      <p>Look for dents on metal gutters, downspouts, and AC units — these are the clearest ground-level indicators. On the roof itself, hail leaves random circular bruise marks on shingles where granules have been knocked off, exposing the dark asphalt mat underneath. A licensed contractor needs to get on the roof to assess properly.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Does insurance cover hail damage to my roof in Utah?</h3>
      <p>Yes — most Utah homeowners insurance policies cover hail damage under dwelling coverage. You pay your deductible (typically $1,000–$2,500); your insurer pays the rest. You generally have 12 months from the storm event to file a claim, though policies vary.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How soon after a hailstorm should I get my roof inspected?</h3>
      <p>As soon as possible — ideally within a few weeks. The 12-month insurance window starts from the storm date, not when you notice damage. After a major SLC storm, licensed contractors book up fast.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What does hail damage roof repair cost in Salt Lake County?</h3>
      <p>Partial hail damage repairs typically run $1,500–$4,500. Full replacement averages $9,000–$20,000 for a standard home. If covered by insurance, your out-of-pocket is your deductible.</p>
    </div>

